      "## list\n\n`client.addresses.list(filter?: { address_book?: { eq?: string; }; customer_reference?: string | { contains?: string; eq?: string; }; street_address?: { contains?: string; }; used_as_emergency?: string; }, page[number]?: number, page[size]?: number, sort?: 'created_at' | 'first_name' | 'last_name' | 'business_name' | 'street_address'): { id?: string; address_book?: boolean; administrative_area?: string; borough?: string; business_name?: string; country_code?: string; created_at?: string; customer_reference?: string; extended_address?: string; first_name?: string; last_name?: string; locality?: string; neighborhood?: string; phone_number?: string; postal_code?: string; record_type?: string; street_address?: string; updated_at?: string; validate_address?: boolean; }`\n\n**get** `/addresses`\n\nReturns a list of your addresses.\n\n### Parameters\n\n- `filter?: { address_book?: { eq?: string; }; customer_reference?: string | { contains?: string; eq?: string; }; street_address?: { contains?: string; }; used_as_emergency?: string; }`\n  Consolidated filter parameter (deepObject style). Originally: filter[customer_reference][eq], filter[customer_reference][contains], filter[used_as_emergency], filter[street_address][contains], filter[address_book][eq]\n  - `address_book?: { eq?: string; }`\n  - `customer_reference?: string | { contains?: string; eq?: string; }`\n    If present, addresses with <code>customer_reference</code> containing the given value will be returned. Matching is not case-sensitive.\n  - `street_address?: { contains?: string; }`\n  - `used_as_emergency?: string`\n    If set as 'true', only addresses used as the emergency address for at least one active phone-number will be returned. When set to 'false', the opposite happens: only addresses not used as the emergency address from phone-numbers will be returned.\n\n- `page[number]?: number`\n\n- `page[size]?: number`\n\n- `sort?: 'created_at' | 'first_name' | 'last_name' | 'business_name' | 'street_address'`\n  Specifies the sort order for results. By default sorting direction is ascending. To have the results sorted in descending order add the <code> -</code> prefix.<br/><br/>\nThat is: <ul>\n  <li>\n    <code>street_address</code>: sorts the result by the\n    <code>street_address</code> field in ascending order.\n  </li>\n\n  <li>\n    <code>-street_address</code>: sorts the result by the\n    <code>street_address</code> field in descending order.\n  </li>\n</ul> <br/> If not given, results are sorted by <code>created_at</code> in descending order.\n\n### Returns\n\n- `{ id?: string; address_book?: boolean; administrative_area?: string; borough?: string; business_name?: string; country_code?: string; created_at?: string; customer_reference?: string; extended_address?: string; first_name?: string; last_name?: string; locality?: string; neighborhood?: string; phone_number?: string; postal_code?: string; record_type?: string; street_address?: string; updated_at?: string; validate_address?: boolean; }`\n\n  - `id?: string`\n  - `address_book?: boolean`\n  - `administrative_area?: string`\n  - `borough?: string`\n  - `business_name?: string`\n  - `country_code?: string`\n  - `created_at?: string`\n  - `customer_reference?: string`\n  - `extended_address?: string`\n  - `first_name?: string`\n  - `last_name?: string`\n  - `locality?: string`\n  - `neighborhood?: string`\n  - `phone_number?: string`\n  - `postal_code?: string`\n  - `record_type?: string`\n  - `street_address?: string`\n  - `updated_at?: string`\n  - `validate_address?: boolean`\n\n### Example\n\n```typescript\nimport Telnyx from 'telnyx';\n\nconst client = new Telnyx();\n\n// Automatically fetches more pages as needed.\nfor await (const address of client.addresses.list()) {\n  console.log(address);\n}\n```",
