    markdown:
      "## send_dtmf\n\n`client.calls.actions.sendDtmf(call_control_id: string, digits: string, client_state?: string, command_id?: string, duration_millis?: number): { data?: call_control_command_result; }`\n\n**post** `/calls/{call_control_id}/actions/send_dtmf`\n\nSends DTMF tones from this leg. DTMF tones will be heard by the other end of the call.\n\n**Expected Webhooks:**\n\nThere are no webhooks associated with this command.\n\n\n### Parameters\n\n- `call_control_id: string`\n\n- `digits: string`\n  DTMF digits to send. Valid digits are 0-9, A-D, *, and #. Pauses can be added using w (0.5s) and W (1s).\n\n- `client_state?: string`\n  Use this field to add state to every subsequent webhook. It must be a valid Base-64 encoded string.\n\n- `command_id?: string`\n  Use this field to avoid duplicate commands. Telnyx will ignore any command with the same `command_id` for the same `call_control_id`.\n\n- `duration_millis?: number`\n  Specifies for how many milliseconds each digit will be played in the audio stream. Ranges from 100 to 500ms\n\n### Returns\n\n- `{ data?: { result?: string; }; }`\n\n  - `data?: { result?: string; }`\n\n### Example\n\n```typescript\nimport Telnyx from 'telnyx';\n\nconst client = new Telnyx();\n\nconst response = await client.calls.actions.sendDtmf('call_control_id', { digits: '1www2WABCDw9' });\n\nconsole.log(response);\n```",
